did.head: DESCRIPTIVE SUMMARY
did.repository: Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections, Cornell University Library
did.abstract: This collection includes the corporate and grant making records of The Atlantic Philanthropies as well as the business records of many of the executives and program officers. The collection includes paper and electronic files.

bioghist.head: ORGANIZATIONAL HISTORY
bioghist.p: The Atlantic Philanthropies were founded by entrepreneur Charles F. ("Chuck") Feeney, a member of the Cornell University Class of 1956. Feeney, whose fortune stemmed from Duty Free Shoppers, decided in 1982 to devote his wealth to creating opportunity for others. Feeney's commitment to Giving While Living, the belief that people of wealth should use it to better the world during their lifetimes, has influenced Atlantic's grant making choices as well as the decision to limit Atlantic's life to a fixed term. The Atlantic Philanthropies will make final grants by December 31, 2016 and plans to close its doors in 2020, by which time nearly $8 billion will have been invested in people, programs, and capital projects around the world. Grant awards to Cornell University total nearly $1 billion from 1982 through 2016.

scopecontent.head: COLLECTION DESCRIPTION
scopecontent.p: This collection includes the corporate and grant making records of The Atlantic Philanthropies as well as the business records of many of the executives and program officers. The collection includes paper and electronic files.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions:
accessrestrict.p: Access to collection restricted until completion of processing.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: “Titles for grant files include the program area and Foundation Center themes assigned to each grant by the Atlantic Philanthropies on their website. Often included are notes from the archivist regarding processing, contents, and restrictions.”
